<subSubSection lastPageId="46" lastPageNumber="47" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" type="key">
<paragraph blockId="45.[151,1437,1906,2042]" lastBlockId="46.[151,1436,153,287]" lastPageId="46" lastPageNumber="47" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,410,1906,1933]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">
Key (
<bibRefCitation author="Wood, S. L." box="[260,397,1906,1933]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" refId="ref46297" refString="Wood, S. L. (2007) Bark and ambrosia beetles of South America (Coleoptera, Scolytidae). Brigham Young University Press, Provo, Utah, 900 pp." type="book" year="2007">Wood 2007</bibRefCitation>
).
</emphasis>
Does not match the first couplet due to the presence of an additional mesal tooth on protibiae and a long, raised interstriae 10. In the key to North American species (
<bibRefCitation author="Wood, S. L." box="[955,1090,1943,1969]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" pagination="1 - 1359" refId="ref46257" refString="Wood, S. L. (1982) The bark and ambrosia beetles of North and Central America (Coleoptera: Scolytidae), a taxonomic monograph. Great Basin Naturalist Memoirs, 6, 1 - 1359." type="journal article" year="1982">Wood 1982</bibRefCitation>
), one may reach to couplet 42, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Wood" authorityYear="1961" box="[151,298,1979,2006]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Scolytodes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="reticulatus">
<emphasis box="[151,298,1979,2006]" italics="true" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">S. reticulatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(not included in 
<bibRefCitation author="Wood, S. L." box="[489,622,1979,2005]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" refId="ref46297" refString="Wood, S. L. (2007) Bark and ambrosia beetles of South America (Coleoptera, Scolytidae). Brigham Young University Press, Provo, Utah, 900 pp." type="book" year="2007">Wood 2007</bibRefCitation>
), but differs as noted in the diagnosis. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,2015,2041]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">Etymology.</emphasis>
The Latin name 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Jordal and Smith" authorityYear="2020" box="[533,640,2015,2041]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Scolytodes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="peniculus">
<emphasis box="[533,640,2015,2041]" italics="true" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">peniculus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is originally a diminutive form of 
<emphasis box="[1044,1103,2016,2041]" italics="true" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">penis</emphasis>
, but is here used as a proper noun (masculine, nominative), meaning dust brush or painter’s brush, referring to the protruding brush of setae in the female frons.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
